In Wuhan on February 12, 2020, there were an estimated 3,509 unquarantined infected cases, which decreased to 334 by February 21, 2020. Based on data up to February 21, we predict that COVID-19 will likely end in Wuhan and Hunan by late March, in the rest of China by mid-March, and in the four tier-one cities before early March 2020. The total estimated number of infected individuals in China is 80,511, with 49,510 in Wuhan, 17,679 in Hunan (excluding Wuhan), and 13,322 in other regions of China. These estimates are based on a deterministic ODE model and should be interpreted with some uncertainty. Recommendations include maintaining strict quarantine and control measures until early March in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Shenzhen, and until late March in Hunan. 

This model may also be useful for predicting the epidemic trend and providing guidance for other countries at high risk of outbreak. The coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) presents unique challenges, with characteristics such as high infectivity during incubation and intervention effects of quarantine measures. The SUQC model was developed to analyze the dynamics of COVID-19 and predict epidemic trends. This model can also offer guidance for countries facing a high risk of outbreak, such as South Korea, Japan, and Iran. This study was conducted by Higher Education Press and Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature in 2020.
